        "Node name for S&R": "CLIPTextEncode"
      },
      "widgets_values": [
        "Anime manga style panoramic photograph capturing a vast mountainous landscape at golden hour, featuring dramatic layered clouds with sunlight breaking through from the right to illuminate the valley below. In the foreground, lush green vegetation with detailed tree foliage and grassy terrain, including some foliage with visible yellow flowers on the left edge. Midground showcases a sprawling valley with a distant cityscape, including buildings, roads, and infrastructure, set against rolling hills and low mountains. Background consists of towering mountain peaks extending to the horizon under a sky filled with textured, layered clouds. Warm golden rays from the sun illuminate the valley and create a balance between warm and cool tones in the scene. The color palette features deep blues and greys for the mountains and sky, warm golds and oranges for the sunlight and illuminated clouds, and rich greens for the vegetation. The entire scene is rendered with highly detailed textures, vibrant color contrast, and a serene yet majestic atmosphere."
      ],
      "color": "#232",
      "bgcolor": "#353"
    },
    {
      "id": 127,
      "type": "Note",
      "pos": [
        2140,
        -310
      ],
      "size": [
        460,
        1500
      ],
      "flags": {},
      "order": 2,
      "mode": 0,
      "inputs": [],
      "outputs": [],
      "properties": {},
      "widgets_values": [
        "While LTXV-2b model prefers long descriptive prompts, this version supports experimentation with broader prompting styles.\n\n1. \nAdjust Temporal Attention Nodes\nIf you are using a workflow that includes a Temporal Attention node, modify these specific parameters to \"lock\" the camera:\n\nIncrease cross_structural: Raising this value helps the model maintain the structural integrity of the scene across frames, effectively throttling unwanted camera shifts.\n\nIncrease self_structural: This reinforces the consistency of the subject and background, preventing the model from hallucinating new perspectives.\n\nLower CFG: High Classifier-Free Guidance (CFG) often introduces \"energy\" that leads to camera movement. Lowering CFG to a range of 2.0 to 4.0 can result in a more stable, stationary shot. \n\n2. \nConfigure the LTXV Scheduler/Model Node\nThe following mathematical shifts in the scheduler can significantly reduce movement:\n\nDecrease max_shift: Bringing this value down reduces the overall range of motion the model is allowed to generate.\nSet terminal to 0: Setting the terminal value to zero helps stabilize the motion toward the end of the clip.\n\nDisable stretch: Turning off the \"stretch\" setting (if available in your node) can help maintain pixel clarity and prevent the \"wobble\" often associated with AI camera movement. \n\n3. \nWorkflow & Prompting Techniques\nUse a Static Reference Image: Start with a high-quality reference image in an Image-to-Video (I2V) workflow. This provides a \"ground truth\" that anchors the spatial coordinates of the scene.\n\nSelect \"Static\" Presets: If you are using the LTX Studio platform, explicitly select the Static camera motion preset from the generation space.\n\nRefine the Prompt: Avoid words that imply action or cinematic transitions. Use descriptive keywords like \"static shot,\" \"fixed camera,\" \"locked-off,\" or \"stationary\" at the beginning and end of your prompt to reinforce the lack of movement. "
      ],
      "color": "#432",
      "bgcolor": "#653"
    },
